					<h3>I Shall Not Be Moved</h3>
					<p>Poetry is an art and extremely powerful. An author can express a great amount of wisdom, knowledge, or feelings in a single poem.
					In the book "I Shall Not Be Moved", Maya Angelou expresses her feelings about situations she was put through in life. Maya Angelou was a poet, a memorist and a civil rights activist. 
					Angelou talks about many controversial topics in her poems such as <i>"The Black Family Pledge"</i>, <i></i>"I know why the caged bird sings", and "Equality". In these poems and throughout her life Angelou protected minorities, women, the young, and the ignored.
					Whether talking about the scourge of discrimination or the evil of sexism, she has much to teach this generation and generations unborn about what it means to be a unique person, and the power of being genuine.
					Although she has passed away, her stories and poems will continue to address students of all ages, and inspire the end of racial discrimination for generations to come.
					<br><br>
